  • Developed from pedagogy
  • Inspired by parallels with 20th-century magical realism movement

  • Implication: hagiographies are governed by rules for their depiction of both worldly and miraculous events

Thank you!

Roman Identity in Transition from the Arab Conquests to the Triumph of Orthodoxy

  • Focus of DFG stipendiary fellowship at University of T?bingen (through 30 April).
  • Under contract with Palgrave-Macmillan. On track for submission in mid-May.

Abstract: This work offers a necessary correction to a set of entrenched distortions in the way historians have read Roman identity in the period. I show that Roman identity remained relevant as a social and political identity in the seventh, eighth, and early ninth centuries AD. In contrast to long-established views, I demonstrate that there is continuity of Roman group identity in the Eastern Mediterranean throughout these centuries. My book is set apart by its tight chronological focus, explicitly delving into one of the most historiographically-challenging periods of the history of the Roman people.
